        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
        "assistant": "### First, a renewed caveat\nAs I noted last turn, **\"coinage probe\" is not an established technical term**. I shouldn't have introduced it in my first reply as if it were. So any contrast I draw here is between (a) what the phrase *would plausibly mean* if used compositionally, and (b) the genuinely established notions of behavioral probing and capability evaluation. Treat the \"coinage probe\" column as a reconstruction, not a citation.\n\n### Behavioral Probe\nIn NLP and cognitive modeling, a **behavioral probe** studies a system (model or human) by examining its **input–output behavior** rather than its internal states. Examples:\n\n- **Linzen, Dupoux & Goldberg (2016)**: testing whether LSTMs handle subject–verb agreement by measuring next-word probabilities on minimal pairs.\n- **BLiMP (Warstadt et al. 2020)**: a benchmark of acceptability minimal pairs probing grammatical knowledge behaviorally.\n- **Psycholinguistic-style tests** on LMs: garden-path sentences, filler-gap dependencies, etc.\n\nThe defining feature: no peeking inside the model. You manipulate inputs, observe outputs, and infer competence.\n\n### Capability Evaluation\nIn contemporary ML (especially LLM evaluation and AI safety), a **capability evaluation** asks whether a model **can perform some task** at some threshold of competence. Examples:\n\n- MMLU, GSM8K, HumanEval, ARC, GPQA — benchmark suites.\n- Dangerous-capability evals (e.g., METR, Anthropic's, DeepMind's) for things like autonomous replication, cyber, bio uplift.\n- Agentic task suites (SWE-bench, WebArena).\n\nThe defining feature: aggregate performance on a defined task, often scored against ground truth, framed in terms of *what the system can do*.\n\n### \"Coinage Probe\" (reconstructed)\nIf the phrase is used at all, it most plausibly denotes a **stimulus-level technique**: presenting a *novel coinage* (an invented word) and seeing what the speaker/model does with it — accept it, parse it, define it, inflect it. The classic instance is Berko's **wug test**.\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Dimension | \"Coinage Probe\" | Behavioral Probe | Capability Evaluation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Established term? | No | Yes | Yes |\n| Granularity | A single stimulus type (novel words) | A method (input–output testing) | A measurement program (task + metric) |\n| Object of study | Morphological/phonological/lexical productivity | Any competence inferable from behavior | Task performance, often aggregated |\n| Output | Judgment, gloss, inflection | Acceptability, probability, choice | Score, pass/fail, accuracy |\n| Typical scale | One item or small set | Curated minimal-pair sets | Large benchmarks |\n| Goal | Diagnose word-formation knowledge | Diagnose specific linguistic/cognitive competence | Quantify capability, often for comparison or risk assessment |\n\n### How they nest\nRoughly:\n\n- A **coinage probe** is a *kind of* behavioral probe (stimulus → judgment, no internals).\n- A **behavioral probe** is one *methodology* that can feed into a **capability evaluation** — but capability evals also include task-completion measures that aren't really \"probes\" in the diagnostic sense (e.g., did the agent ship the pull request?).\n- A **probing classifier** (last turn's topic) sits orthogonally: it inspects *representations*, not behavior.\n\n### A useful distinction\n- **Probing classifier**: \"Is information X *encoded* in the representations?\"\n- **Behavioral probe**: \"Does the system *behave as if* it knows X?\"\n- **Capability evaluation**: \"Can the system *do* task T, and how well?\"\n- **Coinage probe** (if meaningful): \"Does the system extend its lexical/morphological system to novel forms?\"\n\nIf you have a specific source using \"coinage probe,\" I'd still be curious to see it — the contrast might sharpen considerably once we know what the author actually meant.",
