      {
        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from lexical-acquisition test?",
        "assistant": "### Same caveat, one more time\n**\"Coinage probe\" is still not an established term.** I'm reconstructing what it would plausibly mean (a stimulus-based test using invented words to probe productive lexical/morphological knowledge — essentially a wug-test-style technique). The contrast below is between that reconstruction and the genuinely established family of **lexical-acquisition tests**.\n\n### Lexical-Acquisition Test\nA **lexical-acquisition test** measures whether — and how — a learner (child, L2 learner, or model) **acquires** words: their forms, meanings, and usage. The \"learner\" framing is central. Established examples:\n\n- **Receptive vocabulary tests**: PPVT (Peabody Picture Vocabulary Test), BPVS — point-to-the-picture tasks measuring known words.\n- **Productive vocabulary measures**: MacArthur–Bates CDI (parent checklists for infants/toddlers), expressive naming tasks.\n- **Fast-mapping paradigms** (Carey & Bartlett 1978): expose a child once or twice to a novel word in context, later test retention of form–meaning mapping.\n- **Cross-situational word learning** (Yu & Smith 2007): learners track word–referent co-occurrences across ambiguous scenes.\n- **In NLP**: few-shot word-learning evals for LMs (e.g., definitional probes, Lazaridou et al. on novel-word learning), or benchmarks like the Children's Book Test in spirit.\n\nThe defining features: (i) the focus is on **acquisition** — encoding a new form–meaning pair — and (ii) the measured outcome is typically **knowledge of a specific word** after exposure.\n\n### \"Coinage Probe\" (reconstructed)\nA coinage probe, in the wug-test tradition, doesn't ask whether a learner has *acquired* a word. It asks whether the speaker can **extend existing productive machinery** (morphology, phonotactics, semantic composition) to a form they've **never been taught and won't retain**. The novel word is a disposable diagnostic stimulus, not a learning target.\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Dimension | \"Coinage Probe\" (reconstructed) | Lexical-Acquisition Test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Established term? | No | Yes |\n| Core question | \"Can you extend your system to a novel form *right now*?\" | \"Have you (or can you) *learn* this new word?\" |\n| Role of the novel word | Disposable stimulus | Learning target |\n| Exposure | Typically single-shot, no learning expected | Exposure phase + test phase; retention matters |\n| Time course | Instantaneous judgment | Acquisition over time (minutes to years) |\n| What's being measured | Productivity of existing knowledge | Growth of the lexicon |\n| Typical population | Anyone with mature grammar (and children, for development) | Especially children, L2 learners, or models being trained/prompted |\n| Canonical example | Wug test (Berko 1958) | PPVT; fast-mapping; CDI |\n\n### How they relate\nThey overlap but aim at different things:\n\n- A **wug test given to a 4-year-old** is a coinage probe (does the child apply the plural rule to *wug*?) but it's also informative about the *state of acquisition* of English morphology. So coinage probes can serve developmental/acquisition research without being acquisition tests in the strict sense.\n- A **fast-mapping study** uses novel words too, but the point is whether the child *retains* the form–meaning link after exposure — that's acquisition, not productivity.\n- For LLMs, an **in-context novel-word learning eval** (teach the model \"to dax means to X,\" then test usage) is a lexical-acquisition test. A **morphological generalization probe** (\"here's a new verb *dax*; what's its past tense?\") is closer to a coinage probe.\n\n### One-line distinction\n- **Coinage probe**: diagnose **productive competence** via a throwaway novel form.\n- **Lexical-acquisition test**: diagnose **lexical learning** — whether a new form–meaning pair has entered (or can enter) the learner's lexicon.\n\nThe cleanest diagnostic question to tell them apart: *Is the novel word meant to be remembered?* If yes, it's an acquisition test. If no — it's there only to expose what the system already does — it's a coinage/wug-style probe.",
